<section xid="4" props="page-margin-footer:0.5000in; page-margin-header:0.5000in; page-margin-right:1.0000in; page-margin-left:1.0000in; page-margin-top:1.0000in; page-margin-bottom:1.0000in">
<p style="Normal" xid="5"><c props="text-decoration:underline">Richard Dawkins</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="6"><c props="text-decoration:none"></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="7"><c props="text-decoration:none">Richard Dawkins is a materialist. This means that he only believes in what he can verify. </c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="8"><c props="text-decoration:underline">Hard materialists</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="10"><c props="text-decoration:none">Only things that we can verify are true. Dawkins would be described as a hard or scientific materialist. Someone who would argue that there is no part of a person that is not material. He distinguishes between soul 1 and soul 2. Soul 1 is the spiritual soul, which he dismisses. But he believes in soul 2, which is a person’s character and their beliefs. He recognises that this is an element of a person that we call the soul. He is in awe of the process of evolution. For him this is awe-inspiring.  </c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="11"><c props="text-decoration:underline">Soft materialists</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="13"><c props="text-decoration:none">There might be something beyond, and processes that go beyond the purely physical world</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="14"><c props="text-decoration:none"></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="15"><c props="text-decoration:underline">Dawkins’ materialism</c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="17"><c props="text-decoration:underline"></c></p>
<p style="Normal" xid="18"><c props="text-decoration:none">Like Ryle, Dawkins is a materialist, like Ryle, he would also argue that substance dualism is a pre-scientific myth. We now have a much more acute understanding of consciousness, DNA and other things. Pre-scientific attempts to explain consciousness should be rejected. The body is a survival machine, it’s role is to pass on genes, there’s no function or explanation for a material soul. He describes humans as robot vehicles. ‘there is no spirit driven life force, no throbbing, heaving, pululating protoplasmic mystic jelly. Life is just bytes and bytes and bytes of digital information. We pass more developed brains onto the next generation. Dawkins does not believe that we can understand the consciousness with the current science. Thomas Nagel, ‘what it is like to be a bat’. He argues that we could study bats in great detail, you try to become a bat, but we could never know what it is like to be a bat. We can never know what it is like to be someone else, even if we know everything about them, we could still never know what it is like to be in their consciousness. It is that which is what scientists call qualia. </c></p>
</section>
